d has serious implications for social work with homeless youth. Youth in motion have become socially invisible and marginalized from public spaces where social workers traditionally contact them, jeopardizing their access to the already limited opportunities to escape street life. The culmination of a multi-year ethnographic investigation into the lives of street outreach workers and 'their kids' on the streets of New York City, Street Kids illustrates the critical role that public space regulations and policing play in shaping the experience of youth homelessness and the effectiveness of street outreach.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aHomeless youthxNew York (State)xNew York. 0aHomeless youthzNew York (State)zNew York. 0aPolice services for the homelessxNew York (State)xNew YorkxNew York (State)xNew York. 0aPolice services for the homelesszNew York (State)zNew York. 0aSocial work with the homelessxNew York (State)xNew York. 0aSocial work with the homelesszNew York (State)zNew York. 0aSocial work with youthxNew York (State)xNew York. 0aSocial work with youthzNew York (State)zNew York. 0aStreet youthxNew York (State)xNew York. 0aStreet youthzNew York (State)zNew York. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Urban.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP Backlist 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814733370423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814733370.jpg  a978-3-11-070644-4  NYUP Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK